From personal experience (2 weeks in Nepal in 2008), even above-average meals in Nepal are nowhere near as good as what you get at Himal Chuli.
That being said, the prices at this Madison gem are shockingly high.
It is not so much that I expect "ethnic" food to be cheap (I do not), but that the location, ambience, and portion sizes do not match the price tag.
If you can ignore the prices, the food is a real treat.
The momos are delicious (sadly, there is no pan fried variety on the menu), the dal divine, and the roti flavorful.
Fortunately, my wife ordered the combination platter which allowed me to sample the mimochas (very good).
I opted for the stewed jackfruit accompanied by 4 slices of whole wheat roti.
I had not had cooked jackfruit before but dare say that I am a fan.
It tastes almost like an artichoke heart but denser and larger.
Himal Chuli is well worth your while if you are not overly price sensitive and hankering after some good Nepalese food.

